<li id="c76">
  <div class="cx" id="cx51129816">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">Dems don't fear the likes of a Ted Cruz</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1233057/51129816#c76?mode=alone;showrate=1#c76">3+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


<div class="crs"><dl>
  <dt>Recommended by:</dt><dd>
  <a href="/user/uid:2138">Yosef 52</a>, <a href="/user/uid:28701">aitchdee</a>, <a href="/user/uid:94098">Van Buren</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>Steve M. nails both Rich Lowry &amp; National Review's Michael Walsh.</p>
<p>Steve M. @ <a href="http://nomoremister.blogspot.com/2013/08/dear-republicans-maybe-we-win.html">No more Mister Nice Blog</a> - Thursday, August 22, 2013</p>
<p><strong>Steve M.:</strong><br /></p>
<blockquote>Republicans are at it again: an ambitious member of their party has them seeing starbursts, primarily because they think this particular Republican terrifies and infuriates us.</blockquote>
<strong>Rich Lowry:</strong>
<blockquote>Democrats and liberal pundits would surely dislike Cruz no matter where he went to school, but his pedigree adds an extra element of shocked disbelief to the disdain....
<p>One of the left's deepest prejudices is that its opponents are stupid, and Cruz tramples on it. Chris Hayes of MSNBC actually says he fears Cruz's brilliance.</p>
</blockquote>
<strong>Steve M.:</strong>
<blockquote>(Try to follow the logic of that last bit: People on the left think all conservatives are stupid, as evidenced by ... a prominent left-leaning commentator saying that Cruz is actually very smart. Yup, makes sense to me.)</blockquote>
<strong>National Review Michael Walsh</strong>:
<blockquote>Cruz and Rand has already thrown the Left off its game, which is why it's reacted to Cruz like screeching vampires suddenly confronting a crucifix. They want to turn him into the male Sarah Palin, but there’s those pesky little details like his Senate seat and his Harvard pedigree....</blockquote>
<strong>Steve M.:</strong>
<blockquote>No, we don't want to turn Ted Cruz into the male Sarah Palin, because we didn't turn Sarah Palin into the female Sarah Palin -- she did that to herself, which is more or less what we expect Ted Cruz to do<br />
[...]<br />
Cruz is smarter than Palin -- a low bar to clear -- but he's naive if he thinks the road to the White House passes through the Valley of World Net Daily Talking Points.<br />
[...]<br />
But what is it with Republicans and their obsessive quest for the ultimate Dem-destroying nominee?</blockquote>
<p>Rebublicans fall all over the likes of &nbsp;Herman Cain and before that Donald Trump and Sarah Palin. And many of them hoped that Trump or Ben Carson or Allen West or Cruz will be the nominee, <strong>just because they talk a lot of trash about Democrats and liberals.</strong></p>
<p><strong>Steve M.:</strong></p>
<blockquote>But they drive the eventual [republican] winner very, very far to the right, and quite possibly (in 2008 and 2012) to defeat.</blockquote>
Dems otoh want their candidate to fight for our progressive values, not to spend their time earning their keep bashing the likes of a Ted Cruz.
<p>Who also will also never be President.</p>
<p>That's why we don't fear him. We appreciate the exposure he's bringing. The suppuration will suface, to be cleansed out of our county's system</p>
<p><strong>Thx Jed Lewison</strong></p>

  </div>
  <div class="cf">
  <p class="sig"></p>
  <p class="cb">by <a href="/user/uid:231987">Eric Nelson</a> on <a href="/comments/1233057/51129816#c76">Thu Aug 22, 2013 at 08:36:05 PM PDT</a></p>
  <p class="cl">
  
 
 
  
    
   

 
 
 </p> 
